      en: "I'd like to describe Tết Nguyên Đán — the Vietnamese Lunar New Year — which is by far the most significant celebration in Vietnamese culture and the one I look forward to most throughout the year.\n\nTết typically falls in late January or early February, depending on the lunar calendar, and the celebrations effectively span several weeks — from the preparations in the days leading up to it through to the Tết holidays themselves, which last at least three days and often longer for extended family gatherings.\n\nThe preparations are almost as significant as the festival itself. Families undertake thorough house cleaning, symbolising the sweeping away of bad luck from the previous year. Homes are decorated with yellow apricot blossoms or pink peach blossoms, red decorations, and kumquat trees loaded with fruit. Special foods are prepared — most importantly bánh chưng, a traditional square rice cake with pork filling wrapped in banana leaves, which takes hours to cook. On New Year's Eve, families gather for a large ancestral meal, setting out offerings for deceased relatives and giving thanks for the year passed.\n\nDuring the holiday itself, children receive red envelopes containing lucky money from relatives, and families visit each other to exchange good wishes. Temples are crowded with people praying for good fortune in the coming year.\n\nTết is important to me for several interconnected reasons. Most fundamentally, it is the one time each year when our entire extended family — scattered across different cities — comes together in one place. The combination of ritual, food, family, and collective hope for the future creates a uniquely powerful atmosphere that I find genuinely moving every single year.",
