      en: "I'd like to talk about Marie Curie, the Polish-French physicist and chemist, who I consider one of the most genuinely inspiring figures in modern history.\n\nMarie Curie lived from 1867 to 1934 and made extraordinary scientific contributions that fundamentally advanced human understanding of radioactivity — a term she herself coined. She discovered two new elements, polonium and radium, and became the first person in history to win Nobel Prizes in two different scientific disciplines: physics in 1903 and chemistry in 1911.\n\nHer achievements were remarkable in absolute scientific terms, but they become even more extraordinary when considered in context. She pursued her research during a period when women were widely excluded from formal scientific institutions and higher education. She was initially barred from attending university in Poland and had to study secretly through the underground 'Flying University.' When she later moved to Paris and gained access to proper scientific facilities, she consistently faced gender discrimination — yet her scientific output surpassed that of virtually all her male contemporaries.\n\nI find her inspiring for several deeply interconnected reasons. She demonstrated that intellectual excellence combined with disciplined persistence can overcome institutional barriers that seem insuperable. She also showed extraordinary moral integrity: she refused to patent her discoveries, believing that scientific knowledge should be freely accessible to all of humanity. Perhaps most poignantly, she continued working right up until her death — ultimately caused by the very radiation she had spent her career studying — never allowing discomfort or declining health to interrupt her commitment to discovery.",
