      en: "I'd like to describe the challenge I faced when I transitioned to studying at university after having several years away from formal education.\n\nAfter finishing secondary school, I spent three years working full-time in a variety of jobs before deciding to pursue higher education. By the time I enrolled at university, I was noticeably older than my classmates, out of practice with academic writing and study habits, and genuinely uncertain whether I had the intellectual capacity to succeed in a demanding academic environment.\n\nThe first semester was genuinely difficult. The volume of reading was overwhelming, academic writing conventions felt foreign, and I was acutely aware that my classmates seemed more naturally fluent in the language of academic discourse. I struggled particularly with writing essays that moved beyond descriptive summary to genuine critical analysis — a skill that takes time to develop and isn't always explicitly taught.\n\nI dealt with the challenge through several strategies. I sought out my tutors during office hours and was transparent about my difficulties, which led to genuinely useful guidance on academic writing. I formed a study group with two other students who were also mature returnees, which provided both practical support and a sense of solidarity. I also deliberately spent extra time on my weaker areas rather than retreating to what felt comfortable.\n\nBy the end of the first year, I had not only caught up but found that my work experience actually provided me with contextual understanding and a certain groundedness in my thinking that younger students sometimes lacked. The experience taught me that persistent, targeted effort combined with a willingness to ask for help is almost always sufficient to overcome what initially seems like an insurmountable gap.",
