      en: "I'd like to talk about Beethoven's Symphony No. 9 in D minor — and particularly its final movement, the famous 'Ode to Joy' — which has held extraordinary personal significance for me for many years.\n\nI first heard a full live performance of this symphony when I was seventeen, at a concert my school orchestra performed for the community. Despite knowing the main theme from countless advertisements and cultural references, hearing the full symphony in its proper context was a genuinely transformative experience that I remember vividly to this day.\n\nWhat makes this piece of music so meaningful to me is partly its historical context. Beethoven composed his Ninth Symphony after he had become completely deaf — unable to hear a single note of the music he was writing. Yet the symphony he produced is perhaps the most joyful and triumphant work in the Western classical tradition. The final movement, where human voices join the orchestra for the first time in symphonic history, builds to a conclusion of almost overwhelming intensity. There is something deeply moving about the idea that someone could create something of such profound beauty from within circumstances of such profound loss.\n\nThe piece also has personal resonance because I listened to it during a particularly difficult period in my life, and it served as a kind of emotional anchor — evidence that it is possible to create something transcendent even from a position of apparent limitation. Every time I hear it now, that memory returns alongside the music, making it simultaneously a piece of art and a piece of personal history.",
