      en: "I'd like to talk about Kyoto, Japan, which has been on my travel wish list for a very long time and which I intend to visit within the next few years.\n\nKyoto served as Japan's imperial capital for over a thousand years and remains the cultural heart of the country in many respects. Unlike Tokyo, which has been dramatically reshaped by modernisation, Kyoto has preserved a remarkably intact historic cityscape — ancient Buddhist temples, Shinto shrines, traditional wooden townhouses called machiya, and meticulously maintained gardens that represent centuries of landscape design tradition.\n\nI want to visit Kyoto for several reasons. Intellectually, I'm drawn to the depth and coherence of Japanese aesthetic traditions — the concept of wabi-sabi, which finds beauty in imperfection and transience, the Zen Buddhist influence on garden design and architecture, and the extraordinary attention to craft and material quality that characterises traditional Japanese arts. I want to experience these ideas not as abstractions but as actual places and objects.\n\nPractically, I would spend most of my time in the city's historic districts — particularly Gion, the geisha district, and the Higashiyama temple circuit. I'm especially eager to visit the Fushimi Inari shrine with its thousands of vermilion torii gates climbing the mountain, and the bamboo grove at Arashiyama, which I've seen in photographs but which I suspect can only be fully understood in person.\n\nI would ideally go with a close friend who shares my interest in architecture and history. Sharing the experience of a genuinely extraordinary place with someone whose company you enjoy deeply seems to be the optimal way to travel.",
